1
00:00:00,352 --> 00:00:30,155
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sama sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sama sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sama sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble

2
00:00:30,405 --> 00:00:31,928
and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:33,890 --> 00:00:41,840
So I'm mindful of the fact that one or two people here know very little about Buddhism, and some who know quite a lot.

4
00:00:42,179 --> 00:00:54,996
So I'll try and sort of weave a story that sort of encompasses both, and also talk about the Mahasi and the technique that we're using for the Pasana.

5
00:00:56,814 --> 00:01:01,902
When we practice meditation, I think we have to be clear about three things.

6
00:01:02,963 --> 00:01:07,349
First of all, what does the Buddha mean by right awareness?

7
00:01:09,492 --> 00:01:18,203
And then, how do we maintain that sort of awareness against all the hindrances, how the mind wanders off all the time?

8
00:01:19,927 --> 00:01:23,852
And what is it we're investigating?

9
00:01:24,945 --> 00:01:27,048
What is the process of liberation?

10
00:01:27,409 --> 00:01:28,409
What do we mean by that?

11
00:01:29,650 --> 00:01:31,632
What does the Buddha mean by delusion?

12
00:01:34,816 --> 00:01:38,501
So it's always good to start the story with the Buddha himself.

13
00:01:40,843 --> 00:01:45,028
He lived in what you might call an upper middle class.

14
00:01:48,432 --> 00:01:50,254
Well, I suppose almost nobility.

15
00:01:50,894 --> 00:01:54,278
His father was a head man of a group of people

16
00:01:54,629 --> 00:02:23,420
a tribe called the Sakyas and they were under the local king of Kosala so all the stories about him being a very rich prince and all that is all later stuff but he was brought up as a Kshatriya which is the warrior caste so he would have spent a lot of time learning how to use swords and spears and stuff like that and also governance but it's interesting to remember that he would have been illiterate

17
00:02:24,463 --> 00:02:31,513
Writing as such was coming in, but it was coming in much like it happened in Europe, I believe, in accounts.

18
00:02:32,713 --> 00:02:36,078
Businessmen keeping, business people keeping their accounts.

19
00:02:37,379 --> 00:02:40,903
But that didn't mean, of course, that the language wasn't highly developed.

20
00:02:42,306 --> 00:02:43,687
It was passed on through memory.

21
00:02:43,967 --> 00:02:50,116
So even today in Hinduism, the Rig Veda would be learnt off by heart by the Brahmins.

22
00:02:51,056 --> 00:02:52,299
And it's interesting how they do it.

23
00:02:52,338 --> 00:02:54,200
They first of all teach the child

24
00:02:54,400 --> 00:02:58,685
how to pronounce the syllables, even before they know what it means.

25
00:02:58,925 --> 00:03:00,225
They pronounce the syllables.

26
00:03:00,826 --> 00:03:03,409
And then when they've got it off pat, then they tell them what it means.

27
00:03:04,251 --> 00:03:07,074
And only after they know what it means can they begin to philosophize.

28
00:03:08,074 --> 00:03:09,917
It's completely the opposite to what we do.

29
00:03:11,397 --> 00:03:15,543
We expect people to be philosophers and creative before they've got the basics.

30
00:03:17,123 --> 00:03:19,546
So that's the sort of society you lived in.

31
00:03:19,914 --> 00:03:22,598
And of course there were pleasures, there were lots of pleasures.

32
00:03:23,419 --> 00:03:29,925
And he would have had lots of free time as opposed to, say, the labourers and the lower caste.

33
00:03:29,945 --> 00:03:32,269
The caste system wasn't so rigid in his day.

34
00:03:32,508 --> 00:03:34,592
It was becoming so, but not so rigid.

35
00:03:35,913 --> 00:03:45,383
And it was to the east of him, out in present-day Calcutta, that sort of area, present-day Bihar, that the Brahmins were getting ascendancy.

36
00:03:45,663 --> 00:03:46,344
Before that,

37
00:03:46,949 --> 00:03:51,775
the ruling caste, the warrior caste, would have been considered higher than the Brahmins.

38
00:03:54,397 --> 00:04:00,887
And there would seem to be some sort of disaffection with society going on, much like the hippies of the 70s.

39
00:04:00,907 --> 00:04:14,002
And there were lots of men, mainly men, but often their wives and occasional women, who would leave the homely life, who would leave household life, and live...

40
00:04:14,539 --> 00:04:44,293
very very basic lives out in the forests and come in for alms round so all that was established before the Buddha himself set out there was an established custom of how to live the ascetic life and it's thought to go back right back to the Mahendodaro civilization in the Indus Valley which somehow disappeared and we can't read the

41
00:04:44,728 --> 00:04:45,970
Can't read any of their stuff.

42
00:04:46,750 --> 00:04:57,303
But when the Aryans came down from the north and conquered all that area, it seems as though some of their yogic practices and whatnot passed into their culture.

43
00:04:58,245 --> 00:05:06,954
So it has a very long history, this idea of ascetic practice and building up the powers that the mind has as opposed to the body.

44
00:05:09,076 --> 00:05:13,081
Now at some point he gets fed up with the pleasures and joys of life.

45
00:05:13,973 --> 00:05:16,836
They become insipid, vapid, you might say.

46
00:05:17,937 --> 00:05:28,987
And because of that emptiness, that's one of the underlying reasons for him leaving his household life.

47
00:05:29,007 --> 00:05:33,132
But at a deeper level, it was what we would call an existential crisis.

48
00:05:34,053 --> 00:05:40,120
He came to realise that there was, in fact, sickness, ageing and death, and that's where he was boobied to us.

49
00:05:40,139 --> 00:05:42,242
And it's something I think that comes to all of us,

50
00:05:42,509 --> 00:05:45,791
at the end of youth at some point, you know, that's part of growing up.

51
00:05:47,012 --> 00:05:52,257
And normally speaking, people start taking life a bit more seriously in their late twenties.

52
00:05:53,959 --> 00:06:09,774
Career, marriage, partnership, all that sort of stuff takes on a more serious sort of quality as they, you know, move towards a real involvement in social life, in their life, in the life of society.

53
00:06:10,615 --> 00:06:12,076
So at that time,

54
00:06:12,242 --> 00:06:16,047
these things are sort of on his mind, and it comes to a crisis point.

55
00:06:16,968 --> 00:06:27,459
So he gets permission from his family, his wife, to shoot off and spend some time as an ascetic.

56
00:06:27,480 --> 00:06:38,672
And if, I don't know, I can only presume, this is just a personal presumption, that I was a bit like myself when I left, when I joined the Order.

57
00:06:39,276 --> 00:06:45,545
I said to my mother, who wept bitterly, I don't understand why, that I would just go for three years.

58
00:06:45,646 --> 00:06:47,067
It was just trying it out.

59
00:06:47,648 --> 00:06:51,293
I just needed a bit of space, a bit of time, that sort of stuff.

60
00:06:51,452 --> 00:06:56,300
And then, of course, you get habituated, I suppose.

61
00:06:56,319 --> 00:07:03,949
So anyway, he left with this, shall we say, this deep psychological questioning about life.

62
00:07:04,050 --> 00:07:05,992
And it was something that was in the air.

63
00:07:06,547 --> 00:07:11,672
In that time, one thing they were trying to escape was rebirth.

64
00:07:12,012 --> 00:07:13,353
So it was taken for granted.

65
00:07:13,454 --> 00:07:19,380
Not everybody, there were materialists, but it was taken for granted that you basically got reborn.

66
00:07:19,401 --> 00:07:20,942
And you could be reborn in any realm.

67
00:07:21,122 --> 00:07:22,343
You could be reborn as an animal.

68
00:07:23,144 --> 00:07:32,875
And the idea of being reborn wasn't all that happy an idea, especially back onto the earth, because it just meant going through the same old routine, work,

69
00:07:33,766 --> 00:08:02,894
sickness aging and death so there was a sort of existential fear that ran through the society at that time which fueled this idea of trying to seek something which was beyond that and so when the Buddha left he left already into a set system a set way of being an ascetic set customs can't call them rules more like customs there were regular teachers very well-known teachers of the time

70
00:08:03,617 --> 00:08:15,956
It was one of the pastimes of the age to turn up at the park, at these lovely parks that they had, Bamboo Park and so on, especially on a full moon.

71
00:08:17,038 --> 00:08:21,485
When in the east, for those of you who have been, as you know, you can actually see colour, it's that bright.

72
00:08:22,146 --> 00:08:30,158
And on the full moon they would all go to these parks and listen to the great debates and arguments of these ascetics between each other.

73
00:08:31,199 --> 00:08:33,101
And that was one of their entertainments.

74
00:08:34,144 --> 00:08:36,006
This is before videos and stuff like that.

75
00:08:37,128 --> 00:08:40,431
So he left the home life to join that sort of life.

76
00:08:40,671 --> 00:08:46,596
And the first thing he tries is teachers who teach him how to attain blissful states.

77
00:08:48,239 --> 00:08:50,860
All religions have these blissful states.

78
00:08:50,880 --> 00:08:53,123
They're attained through prayer, through mantra.

79
00:08:56,025 --> 00:09:01,991
And what we discover in that sort of technique, such as the metta we did,

80
00:09:02,562 --> 00:09:07,485
we can build up a very tremendous ecstasy within ourselves.

81
00:09:07,505 --> 00:09:12,571
The heart, although I was saying to you that when we practice metta, we don't worry about the emotions.

82
00:09:13,350 --> 00:09:15,913
It may be not feeling so good.

83
00:09:15,933 --> 00:09:18,115
It may be a bit depressed and whatnot.

84
00:09:18,495 --> 00:09:21,938
But eventually, the heart does begin to resonate with the will.

85
00:09:23,059 --> 00:09:30,005
And as you keep making these very gentle intentions, the heart resonates more and more.

86
00:09:30,485 --> 00:09:31,287
And they become...

87
00:09:31,519 --> 00:09:55,705
quite you know quite internal ecstasies now one of the benefits of being able to develop that sort of thing is that you're happy you're happy while you're in the absorption and when you come out of it it stays with you it's not as though it's not as though that mood suddenly disappears and when you become an adept at such a thing you can move in and out of that at will

88
00:09:56,730 --> 00:10:06,761
And so you can understand how if you're going to find a way of being blissed out all the time, what do you worry about sex, drugs and rock and roll for?

89
00:10:07,201 --> 00:10:09,183
Or food or anything like that?

90
00:10:09,605 --> 00:10:16,893
You're quite happy under a tree with your loincloth and you nip around for a bit of food every day and you don't mind what you eat.

91
00:10:17,613 --> 00:10:22,238
It's immaterial because all you want to do is just sustain the body so you can get back under your tree.

92
00:10:23,379 --> 00:10:23,919
So...

93
00:10:24,119 --> 00:10:34,609
That sort of blissful practice was already well developed, and he brought it into his teaching, and we call them the jhanic states, the absorptions.

94
00:10:35,370 --> 00:10:40,414
And one of those practices is the metta we were doing this morning.

95
00:10:40,434 --> 00:10:53,147
But the problem is that these things do die out, and that underlying them, because they don't deal with problems, they don't deal with psychological problems, they definitely don't deal with the fear's

96
00:10:53,431 --> 00:10:55,573
and the aversion of sickness, aging, and death.

97
00:10:56,596 --> 00:11:06,909
And so whenever these things passed away, whenever the old thoughts returned, he realized that actually that wasn't an escape from suffering.

98
00:11:06,929 --> 00:11:13,299
It was like icing over dung, you might say, if you'll excuse the expression.

99
00:11:13,879 --> 00:11:18,527
So with that, he left his teachers, who taught him these absorptions.

100
00:11:19,991 --> 00:11:28,481
And then he tried, this is the normal chronology that you get taught, you see, but it's not actually absolutely clear which came first.

101
00:11:28,542 --> 00:11:32,427
But anyway, he then tried what's known as the ascetic practices.

102
00:11:33,227 --> 00:11:41,518
The main one was starvation, was really drawing the body down to its limit, you might say.

103
00:11:42,860 --> 00:11:45,763
So there were two major philosophies which...

104
00:11:46,198 --> 00:11:48,101
you can see even these days.

105
00:11:48,162 --> 00:11:56,734
The first was a materialist philosophy, which basically meant that you die, and that's it, that's the end of it, and you may as well enjoy life as much as you can.

106
00:11:57,434 --> 00:12:03,724
And that was the idea of just enjoying the ordinary pleasures of life, but also these absorptions.

107
00:12:04,303 --> 00:12:06,006
At least you enjoyed life.

108
00:12:06,407 --> 00:12:13,977
Some thought that you had these absorptions, and then you went from rebirth to rebirth, right into higher and higher life,

109
00:12:14,211 --> 00:12:19,398
and more subtle levels of peacefulness and joy, and that was it.

110
00:12:19,638 --> 00:12:20,379
Then you disappeared.

111
00:12:20,778 --> 00:12:28,327
So there were all sorts of theories about how life progressed.

112
00:12:28,347 --> 00:12:43,323
And on the other side, as opposed to that sort of nihilistic idea, annihilationist idea, so that everybody just annihilated at one point or another, there were those, of course, who believed in an eternal soul.

113
00:12:45,177 --> 00:12:48,621
And the soul was trapped in the body.

114
00:12:48,942 --> 00:12:51,446
It was trapped by its karma.

115
00:12:51,666 --> 00:12:53,109
Karma had become physical.

116
00:12:53,769 --> 00:12:58,817
It was your body and it was your attraction to the senses that kept you down at this level.

117
00:12:59,418 --> 00:13:12,736
And therefore, if one could let go of this through ascetic practices, then the soul would be released from the body or the desire to be reborn in this realm and it would rise into eternal bliss.

118
00:13:13,375 --> 00:13:16,700
So the Jains were very much into that sort of philosophy.

119
00:13:17,380 --> 00:13:22,668
And it's understood that the Buddha actually worked with them.

120
00:13:22,688 --> 00:13:26,975
He was his elder contemporary, the Jain leader, the Nigantha.

121
00:13:29,158 --> 00:13:38,033
And so the idea was, of course, the main thing was to not give any pleasure to the sense bases, you see.

122
00:13:40,222 --> 00:13:42,687
And he seems to have practiced this quite severely.

123
00:13:42,846 --> 00:13:45,150
He talks about holding his spine through his stomach.

124
00:13:45,772 --> 00:13:47,894
If you have a go at that, you'll see how thin he was.

125
00:13:49,758 --> 00:13:54,784
And at some point, he sort of wakes up and he realizes, actually, this is getting him nowhere either.

126
00:13:55,306 --> 00:13:57,009
And in fact, all it is, is more suffering.

127
00:13:57,590 --> 00:14:04,880
So he leaves his companions and they're quite disgusted with him because they think they've gone soft or he's lost his courage, you know.

128
00:14:05,754 --> 00:14:12,322
Remember that the James Saint, the ones that they really praise are the ones who finally stop eating.

129
00:14:13,182 --> 00:14:20,331
That's the way they would express their saintliness, just to finally stop eating and die, let go.

130
00:14:23,475 --> 00:14:32,184
So we have this rather dejected young man by the roadside and somebody comes along, we actually know her name, Sujata.

131
00:14:32,434 --> 00:14:35,398
It means happy birth, with some offerings for the local god.

132
00:14:35,798 --> 00:14:40,682
Although it's sort of a sweet rice thing, but I much prefer to think of it as rice pudding.

133
00:14:41,543 --> 00:14:50,611
And when she sees this poor wretch, in the scriptures, of course, they talk about her being bowled over by this god-like figure by the roadside.

134
00:14:50,672 --> 00:14:55,297
But, I mean, if he's almost starved himself to death, it can hardly look like that.

135
00:14:56,177 --> 00:14:58,559
Anyway, he eats.

136
00:14:58,878 --> 00:15:04,847
He has this rice pudding, you see, which of course is a break away from all that ascetic practice.

137
00:15:04,868 --> 00:15:06,210
And it sort of revivifies him.

138
00:15:06,590 --> 00:15:12,679
And something happens at that point, which then brings about a turnaround in his practice.

139
00:15:12,759 --> 00:15:16,725
And it's because of this that we say he is self-enlightened.

140
00:15:16,745 --> 00:15:18,428
Up until now, there's no direction.

141
00:15:20,511 --> 00:15:24,077
He remembers his father doing a ploughing ceremony.

142
00:15:24,097 --> 00:15:24,980
And he's a child.

143
00:15:25,581 --> 00:15:26,522
And he remembers...

144
00:15:26,738 --> 00:15:53,285
the state that he was in when he's watching his father doing this ploughing ceremony it's to open the sewing season and he recognizes in that state the same attentiveness the same concentration that he's been able to gain through his practice of the absorption the concentration practice but there is within that also a question mark so there's the child observing his father

145
00:15:53,840 --> 00:16:04,552
completely absorbed in what's happening and with the wonder, like what is this all about, what's going to happen in his mind.

146
00:16:04,572 --> 00:16:10,979
And it's because of that little memory that he turns the whole process of meditation around upon itself.

147
00:16:10,999 --> 00:16:20,909
So instead of trying to find an escape from suffering, trying to find a place where there's no suffering, he turns around upon suffering to ask how suffering is caused in the first place.

148
00:16:21,682 --> 00:16:26,609
And it's with that inspiration that he sits under the Bodhi tree, which is the fig tree.

149
00:16:26,750 --> 00:16:27,671
It's a great big tree.

150
00:16:27,811 --> 00:16:29,413
It's lovely.

151
00:16:29,493 --> 00:16:31,255
On a hot day, you definitely want to sit under it.

152
00:16:32,236 --> 00:16:38,184
And it's there that he sits and makes this what we call the great determination.

153
00:16:39,265 --> 00:16:42,269
So there's the great renunciation when he leaves home.

154
00:16:42,691 --> 00:16:43,432
Everything's greater.

155
00:16:43,991 --> 00:16:46,796
And there's the great determination when he sits under the tree.

156
00:16:47,417 --> 00:16:51,302
And he determines because he sees no other...

157
00:16:51,669 --> 00:17:18,605
no other way of dealing with this existential crisis within himself that he will sit and either he'll crack this problem or he'll die now i always say lucky for him and lucky for us it only took six hours according to the legends that around him and he makes this break he makes this real breakthrough and with it there comes this release from what he termed delusion you see

158
00:17:20,324 --> 00:17:25,349
So let's go back a bit and just talk about this right awareness.

159
00:17:25,611 --> 00:17:27,292
So it's the image of a child.

160
00:17:28,294 --> 00:17:31,678
I usually have a picture hanging up, but I've not had time yet to put it up.

161
00:17:33,220 --> 00:17:44,694
If you bring the image of a child, usually even up to the age of 10 sometimes, 10, 11, and they become absorbed in something, you notice what their face is like.

162
00:17:45,333 --> 00:17:46,894
Their eyes are fixated.

163
00:17:46,913 --> 00:17:51,137
If they see a bug or something they've never seen before, they just become completely absorbed.

164
00:17:51,939 --> 00:17:53,980
They lose a sense of all their surroundings.

165
00:17:54,181 --> 00:17:56,303
You can shout at them, but they're completely absorbed.

166
00:17:57,282 --> 00:17:58,364
And their mouth drops.

167
00:17:58,544 --> 00:18:00,006
They look gormless.

168
00:18:00,246 --> 00:18:05,770
So parents usually tell them to close their mouths or a fly will go in or something.

169
00:18:05,790 --> 00:18:07,893
Give them a clip on the back of the head to tell them to wake up.

170
00:18:08,472 --> 00:18:14,157
And in so doing, of course, ruin that moment, its potential for full liberation, you see.

171
00:18:14,829 --> 00:18:17,653
So just think of that face, you see.

172
00:18:18,032 --> 00:18:25,760
So the fixation of the eyes, the complete absorption, the wonder, the wonder, and the jaw dropping.

173
00:18:26,641 --> 00:18:33,468
When the jaw drops, and this is why we say lips together, teeth apart, the jaw's relaxed, this is connected to your thinking.

174
00:18:34,249 --> 00:18:36,631
So the thinking stops, see.

175
00:18:37,311 --> 00:18:40,855
The thinking stops and there's just the watching, just the observing.

176
00:18:41,746 --> 00:18:49,016
And then when, of course, the child has absorbed what it is they're looking at, the question arises, what is it?

177
00:18:50,657 --> 00:18:53,883
And of course they're told that's a beetle or something.

178
00:18:54,983 --> 00:19:04,738
And as soon as the beetle is known, the word beetle, it attaches itself to an image in the mind that we call a perception.

179
00:19:05,699 --> 00:19:08,563
Every time that child from now on sees a beetle,

180
00:19:09,151 --> 00:19:37,960
it just says there's a beetle it never really looks again and that's where we are we never get down to the direct experience of things because we presume the concept we have of it is a direct perception so even when you look across at the meadows here and you see a tree you'll know it's a tree we see it's a tree but we don't actually look at the tree

181
00:19:38,327 --> 00:19:44,617
in that same original way, the original mind, the beginner's mind of a child.

182
00:19:44,979 --> 00:20:01,787
The whole process of vipassana is to get back to that original mind, to get back to that non-conceptual way, non-thinking way, non-emergetic way of looking, feeling and experiencing things.

183
00:20:03,488 --> 00:20:08,296
And of course very difficult for us because ever since we were children we've been taught the opposite.

184
00:20:10,921 --> 00:20:26,728
The more literate, the more visual, the more we depend upon images, TV, all that sort of stuff, the less actually we're in contact with the sense bases as the sense base itself directly experiences something.

185
00:20:28,311 --> 00:20:36,981
So, for instance, if you go to a restaurant and you decide you're going to have a pizza or something, and you have a pizza, you already have an idea of a pizza.

186
00:20:37,843 --> 00:20:41,727
So the pizza turns up and it's not so good, it's a very good pizza.

187
00:20:42,387 --> 00:20:45,872
It's immediately compared with all the past pizzas.

188
00:20:46,673 --> 00:20:49,935
But this pizza itself is completely original in itself.

189
00:20:51,057 --> 00:20:53,861
And there's an inability to accept it as it is.

190
00:20:54,361 --> 00:20:56,022
It's always in a state of comparison.

191
00:20:57,016 --> 00:21:25,115
which either makes us happy or unhappy so you can see how the mind with its concepts and perceptions and history distorts our present experience now it's not as though we want to get rid of it we do need to know when we see something that it is a car that this is a pizza it's a case of knowing that there's another way of experiencing things and that's this direct contact

192
00:21:25,535 --> 00:21:53,701
