402
00:41:23,920 --> 00:41:25,802
So aversion arises naturally.

403
00:41:26,603 --> 00:41:29,425
And if the enemy is a bit bigger than me, then of course I've got to run for it.

404
00:41:29,786 --> 00:41:31,407
So fear arises naturally.

405
00:41:31,961 --> 00:41:43,992
So these three attitudes is the undercurrent of our lives because of a delusion as to who we are.

406
00:41:45,432 --> 00:41:47,855
Acquisitiveness, greed, aversion and fear.

407
00:41:49,356 --> 00:41:52,378
And from that all the gamut of human misery arises.

408
00:41:53,179 --> 00:42:00,146
All the future unethical actions that we commit and the guilt and the remorse.

409
00:42:00,545 --> 00:42:01,547
Misery, misery all the way.

410
00:42:04,784 --> 00:42:13,092
So our process is twofold, and again I'll try to speak more about that at some future time.

411
00:42:13,672 --> 00:42:24,362
It's both this understanding, this investigation of who we really are, or what we really are, and a process of purification.

412
00:42:25,063 --> 00:42:32,309
Because our relationship, our relationship to each other, to the world, to anything,

413
00:42:32,594 --> 00:42:35,398
Our relationship is our ethics.

414
00:42:35,418 --> 00:42:42,048
The way we relate is the way we are either ethical or unethical.

415
00:42:42,068 --> 00:42:43,630
So it's all connected.

416
00:42:43,972 --> 00:42:45,594
It's all connected.

417
00:42:45,614 --> 00:42:50,621
And so the process of purification is part and parcel of the path.

418
00:42:50,822 --> 00:42:53,346
And that's the hard bit of the practice.

419
00:42:57,452 --> 00:42:58,534
So...

420
00:43:00,150 --> 00:43:02,693
I just wanted to say something just about the Mahasi.

421
00:43:03,155 --> 00:43:12,065
So the Mahasi was a teacher last century, which was a great revival of Buddhist practice.

422
00:43:12,085 --> 00:43:17,172
It had gone sort of dead by the end of the 19th century, so it's said anyway.

423
00:43:17,193 --> 00:43:21,878
But during the last century, many teachers arose, really very great teachers.

424
00:43:23,099 --> 00:43:27,846
And both in the Tibetan and in the Chinese,

425
00:43:28,045 --> 00:43:34,454
And in Japanese tradition, all these traditions, suddenly these very great teachers arose.

426
00:43:34,474 --> 00:43:38,639
And in the Theravada tradition, the Mahasi was definitely one of those.

427
00:43:39,579 --> 00:43:47,210
There's a book written by Jack Confield, which used to be called Living Buddhist Masters, but they're all dead now, apart from one.

428
00:43:48,132 --> 00:43:49,313
So it's been retitled.

429
00:43:49,893 --> 00:43:56,483
And in it, there are, I think, about 10 or 11 masters whom he interviewed.

430
00:43:57,172 --> 00:44:04,259
all of whom had a system through which they would get across the teachings of the Buddha.

431
00:44:05,500 --> 00:44:11,847
Two of them have become, maybe three, have become very regular in the West.

432
00:44:12,606 --> 00:44:21,396
The one is taught more famously by Goenkaji, who died recently, which is one system of vipassana.

433
00:44:22,356 --> 00:44:27,161
The more generalized system is very simple, just watch the breath and whatever arises and passes away

434
00:44:27,782 --> 00:44:57,536
and in that sense it's very close to Zen but the other system is by the Mahasi and whichever Buddhist meditation center you go to if you see people walking slowly then they've been infected with the Mahasi technique and most virtually all the teachers in the Theravada tradition would have practiced in the Mahasi tradition and probably mixed it with other things here

435
00:44:57,753 --> 00:45:04,523
I try to keep it fairly close to its original form.

436
00:45:04,543 --> 00:45:07,827
And there are two parts to the system without going into great detail.

437
00:45:07,907 --> 00:45:10,231
First of all, this noting that we've practiced.

438
00:45:11,032 --> 00:45:17,161
And the idea there, as we've said, is to reduce the thinking mind to a single point.

439
00:45:17,922 --> 00:45:22,429
It also has the ability to make us recognize what's going on.

440
00:45:22,449 --> 00:45:25,954
To really acknowledge what it is that's happening in the body, heart and mind.

441
00:45:26,963 --> 00:45:35,815
And it has this added addition, added benefit that in pointing at something, you're actually recognizing it's not you.

442
00:45:35,855 --> 00:45:41,181
If it's an object, how can it be the subject?

443
00:45:42,103 --> 00:45:44,766
How can the perceiver be the perceived?

444
00:45:44,786 --> 00:45:46,108
How can the knower be the known?

445
00:45:48,451 --> 00:45:53,577
And that separation is part of the process of liberation from

446
00:45:53,862 --> 00:45:57,128
this deep delusion as to who we are, or what we are.

447
00:45:58,068 --> 00:45:58,210
See?

448
00:45:58,971 --> 00:46:02,277
So it's something that you might want to really develop while you're here.

449
00:46:04,780 --> 00:46:11,032
And in a classic Mahasi meditation, which we do for the rest of the year, it's done all the time.

450
00:46:11,072 --> 00:46:12,253
You don't have a break from it.

451
00:46:12,914 --> 00:46:16,360
As soon as you wake up, you're noting, and you keep on noting until you fall asleep.

452
00:46:16,380 --> 00:46:16,460
See?

453
00:46:20,592 --> 00:46:24,496
The other thing is going slow, stopping, stopping and going slow.

454
00:46:24,516 --> 00:46:38,414
So going back to, you know, the old films, but we know from these nature programs when they take pictures of, say, I mean, the one I always remember is the frog and the way it catches a fly.

455
00:46:39,434 --> 00:46:50,329
And because they can speed up the action of the camera these days, they can really slow it all down and you can see the action perfectly, how it does it, you see.

456
00:46:51,085 --> 00:46:55,791
You may be surprised to know that the fly is caught underneath the tongue.

457
00:46:55,811 --> 00:46:56,132
You see?

458
00:46:56,632 --> 00:46:57,574
Did you really know that?

459
00:46:58,295 --> 00:46:59,577
And was it necessary to know it?

460
00:47:00,197 --> 00:47:02,300
But the thing...

461
00:47:02,320 --> 00:47:08,789
But the real, the important thing is that that could not be seen unless the whole process had been slowed down.

462
00:47:09,090 --> 00:47:09,389
You see?

463
00:47:09,971 --> 00:47:10,911
So it's the same with us.

464
00:47:11,273 --> 00:47:13,856
The slower we go, the more we'll see.

465
00:47:14,496 --> 00:47:19,623
Just in the same way as either driving through the countryside, cycling through it, or walking through it.

466
00:47:20,532 --> 00:47:21,952
The slower you go, the more you see.

467
00:47:22,554 --> 00:47:27,458
So really get this feeling that there's plenty of time to do things.

468
00:47:27,739 --> 00:47:29,561
Opening a door.

469
00:47:29,661 --> 00:47:32,284
So this is the last little example I'll leave to you.

470
00:47:33,164 --> 00:47:36,128
Closing doors here is part of the fire regulations.

471
00:47:36,148 --> 00:47:38,329
But for us, it's a much deeper practice.

472
00:47:38,670 --> 00:47:43,695
It's about our existentialist, our existential understandings.

473
00:47:44,496 --> 00:47:50,521
Remember that the person who stands on one side of the room, by the time they've gone out to the door, have changed.

474
00:47:51,784 --> 00:47:57,855
Even in that small moment, whoever was standing there and now is standing here has changed.

475
00:47:58,635 --> 00:48:05,005
It might not be particularly perceptible, but there must have been a change.

476
00:48:05,025 --> 00:48:08,751
So as you approach the door, you see, stand for a moment.

477
00:48:08,771 --> 00:48:11,817
You can just stop for a moment and then intending to open.

478
00:48:12,498 --> 00:48:17,927
And as your arm stretches out, stretching, stretching, as your fingers touch the handles,

479
00:48:18,329 --> 00:48:19,871
You get the feel of it.

480
00:48:20,050 --> 00:48:21,271
The feel of the metal.

481
00:48:21,592 --> 00:48:22,594
Touching, touching.

482
00:48:23,233 --> 00:48:27,179
And as you press the handle, be in communication with the spring.

483
00:48:27,338 --> 00:48:29,942
Neither too much nor too little.

484
00:48:30,762 --> 00:48:33,144
In perfect communication with the spring.

485
00:48:33,606 --> 00:48:35,407
And then pulling as you open the door.

486
00:48:35,947 --> 00:48:37,889
And then stepping and so on and so forth.

487
00:48:38,791 --> 00:48:41,934
And then when you've closed the door, one moment of stopping.

488
00:48:42,735 --> 00:48:44,097
And then the next intention.

489
00:48:45,057 --> 00:48:47,019
Now sometimes you can't do it because people are waiting.

490
00:48:47,336 --> 00:49:14,222
but whenever you can really get into that habit of stopping as many times as you can during the day and just get into that state of just and seeing the next intention and remember that the importance of intentions in Buddhism is that all our conditionings begin with an intention it's when we empower an intention that we produce a habit

491
00:49:15,637 --> 00:49:19,422
And when we have a compendium of habits, we have a personality.

492
00:49:20,804 --> 00:49:24,407
Once you have a personality, your destiny is before you.

493
00:49:25,550 --> 00:49:27,751
Because your habits drive you in a certain way.

494
00:49:28,213 --> 00:49:36,262
So becoming aware of our habits and knowing which habits we want to develop and which habits we want to get rid of is also part of our practice.

495
00:49:38,186 --> 00:49:40,969
And one important practice...

496
00:49:41,235 --> 00:50:08,137
spiritual practice is to stop and be in that state of just being for a change so we've uh we had a quick look through the buddha's life and came to see that because of the memory the child's face see if you can if you can image that before you sit can be a powerful reminder

497
00:50:10,987 --> 00:50:18,014
And that his liberation from suffering, you see, brought about these understandings.

498
00:50:18,715 --> 00:50:24,380
And, lucky for us, a way of teaching it.

499
00:50:25,641 --> 00:50:32,128
We talk about Pacheco Buddhas, Buddhas, private Buddhas, people who've become liberated, but don't leave a dispensation.

500
00:50:32,429 --> 00:50:35,711
Either they don't teach or the opportunity wasn't there, who knows?

501
00:50:36,755 --> 00:50:49,172
So one of the gifts of this particular person, the Siddhartha Gautama, was that he left a systematic way of achieving the end of suffering.

502
00:50:49,192 --> 00:50:58,443
And then we talked about the hindrances, which we'll go into more deeply tomorrow, and how, generally speaking, how to approach them.

503
00:50:58,925 --> 00:51:04,331
And the basic instruction, of course, is to come off the story and stay in the body, stay with the feelings.

504
00:51:06,032 --> 00:51:35,500
and then we talk about the three characteristics sense of impermanence sense of not self and the process of desire we didn't say much about that but we'll cover it in more detail tomorrow so I can only hope my words have been of some assistance may you by your fierce determination achieve full liberation sooner rather than later

505
00:51:36,677 --> 00:51:38,170
Saru.

506
00:51:38,190 --> 00:51:38,916
Saru.

507
00:51:39,400 --> 00:51:40,005
Saru.

